snippet.textDisplay: @Tim Powell I agree that COVID will always be around, but hopefully it will eventually not be as lethal and WILL be more like pneumonia.  About 60,000 people a year die of pneumonia.  COVID has been around for a little over two years and over a million people have died.  No, we can't live our lives doing everything possible to avoid COVID, but we can continue to weigh the risks and take sensible precautions.

snippet.textDisplay: Because getting COVID is still horrible!  My daughter and her family (8 people), and my brother and his family (6 people) all just had it.  They were all vaxxed and boosted, and didn't require medical attention, but they still said it was no fun.  They were all sick for at least ten days, and are still recovering weeks later.  My daughter makes her living focusing with her brain, and she just couldn't do that during the first ten days or she got a severe headache.  She still gets brain fog if she concentrates too long.  And it's not like getting COVID will make you permanently immune.  You can get it again and again and again.  And more cases mean more exposure for people at higher risk.  Seriously, why at this point do you NOT care about cases?
